{{Infobox scientist | name = Sarah P. Monks | image = Sarah P. Monks.jpg | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = 1841 | birth_place = [[Cold Spring, New York]] | death_date = {{nowrap|July 10, 1926 (aged 85)}} | death_place = [[San Pedro, California]] | nationality = American | fields = Zoology | workplaces = [[Los Angeles State Normal School]] | education = [[Vassar College]] | known_for = }} '''Sarah Preston Monks''' (1841–1926) was an American naturalist, educator, scientific illustrator, and poet, based for much of her career in [[San Pedro, California]]. She was the first zoology instructor at [[Los Angeles State Normal School]], a precursor to the [[University of California, Los Angeles]], where she taught for over 20 years, and published on diverse topics including reptiles, amphibians, spiders, and marine biology.
==Early life and education== Sarah Preston Monks was born in [[Cold Spring, New York]], the daughter of John Monks and Sarah Charlotte Monks (née Jolly).<ref>{{cite book|contribution=Monks, John Austin Sands |title=Who's Who in New England|contribution-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TaITAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA659|year=1909|publisher=A.N. Marquis|page=659}}</ref> Her brother [[John A. S. Monks]] became a noted New England artist<ref name="Sunset" /> and her sister Mary E. Monks lived in Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite journal|title=In Memoriam: Sarah Preston Monks|journal=Vassar Quarterly|volume= 12, 1|date=December 1926|page=56|url=https://newspaperarchives.vassar.edu/cgi-bin/vassar?a=d&d=vq19261201-01.2.29&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN--------}}</ref><ref name="Pelletreau1886">{{cite book|first=William S.|last= Pelletreau|title=History of Putnam County, New York: With Biographical Sketches of Its Prominent Men|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tC4IMtVzFnQC&pg=PA760|year=1886|publisher=W.W. Preston|page=760}}</ref> She studied at [[Vassar College]], where she earned a bachelor's degree in 1871 and a master's degree in 1876. She read one of her own poems, "Waiting for the Tide", at Vassar's 1871 graduation ceremony.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vassar College; Commencement Exercises Yesterday|work=The New York Times|date=June 22, 1871|page=1|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1871/06/22/archives/vassar-college-commencement-exercises-yesterdaya-great-crowd-at.html |language=en}}</ref> She pursued further technical training at the [[Woman's Medical College of Pennsylvania]].<ref name="Sunset">{{cite magazine|first=Henrietta|last= Boeckmann|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XUVEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA54|title=Interesting Westerners|magazine=Sunset|date= January 1920|page=54}}</ref>
==Career== [[File:SarahPMonks1920.tif|thumb|Sarah P. Monks, seated, holding a starfish specimen, from a 1920 publication.]] While still in Philadelphia, she worked at the [[Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University|Academy of Natural Sciences]], classifying ornithological specimens. She later moved to California, where she taught for one year at the College of Santa Barbara before joining the faculty of the [[Los Angeles State Normal School]] in 1884 where she became the school's first instructor of zoology.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Centennial Record of the University of California, 1868-1968|contribution=Zoology (Los Angeles)|last=Ball|first=Gordon H.|year=1967|editor-last=Stadtman|editor-first= Verne A.|page=365}}</ref> She taught zoology, chemistry and drawing at the Normal School until her retirement in 1906<ref>Keith Anderson, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7Jp5CgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA140&dq=Sarah%20P.%20Monks&pg=PA140#v=onepage&q=Sarah%20P.%20Monks&f=false ''The Los Angeles State Normal School, UCLA's Forgotten Past: 1881–1919''] (2015): 140, 143. {{ISBN|9781329317192}}</ref> and was curator of the school's museum.<ref name="Knatz">{{cite journal |last1=Knatz |first1=Geraldine |title=Early Women Scientists of Los Angeles Harbor |journal=Bulletin of the Southern California Academy of Sciences |date=2016 |volume=115 |issue=2 |pages=98–111 |doi=10.3160/0038-3872-115.2.98 |url=https://scholar.oxy.edu/scas/vol115/iss2/2}}</ref> She also lectured on entomology and microscopy at the school's Teachers' Institutes (continuing education programs for teachers in Southern California).<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18461324/sarah_p_monks_1888/ "The Teachers"] ''Los Angeles Times'' (April 20, 1888): 8. via [[Newspapers.com]]{{open access}}</ref><ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18461521/sarah_p_monks_1892/ "Teachers' Institute"] ''Los Angeles Herald'' (March 29, 1892): 6. via [[Newspapers.com]]{{open access}}</ref> Meanwhile, she worked on research projects in her own time, and in collaboration with the [[William Emerson Ritter]]'s laboratory on [[Terminal Island]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Knatz |first1=Geraldine |title=The Marine Biological Laboratory at Terminal Island, Los Angeles Harbor |journal=Bulletin of the Southern California Academy of Sciences |date=2016 |volume=115 |issue=2 |pages=84–97 |doi=10.3160/0038-3872-115.2.84}}</ref> She collected specimens and published scientific and popular articles on turtles, lizards, salamanders, spiders, shipworms, and diatoms.<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18461672/sarah_p_monks_1891/ "All About Diatoms"] ''Los Angeles Herald'' (September 6, 1891): 6. via [[Newspapers.com]]{{open access}}</ref> She also published poetry. In her seventies, she consulted on topics including marine biology, entomology, botany, and geology from her cottage and garden in [[San Pedro, Los Angeles|San Pedro]]. "I am pleasing myself as I please," she explained of her unconventional interests. "I have been bossed all my life."<ref name="Sunset" />
Publications by Monks included the textbook ''Anatomy Physiology Hygiene'' (though she was not credited as author of this text, only as illustrator), "A Partial Biography of the Green Lizard" (''The American Naturalist'', 1881),<ref>Sarah P. Monks, [https://books.google.com/books?id=vyzyAAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA96&ots=N8U9CYK1AN&dq=Sarah%20P.%20Monks&pg=PA96#v=onepage&q=Sarah%20P.%20Monks&f=false "A Partial Biography of the Green Lizard"] ''The American Naturalist'' (February 1881): 96-99.</ref> "Regeneration of the Body of a Starfish" (''Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia'', 1903),<ref>Sarah P. Monks, [https://archive.org/details/jstor-4062904 "Regeneration of the Body of a Starfish"] ''Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia'' 55(1903): 351.</ref> "Variability and Autotomy of Phataria" (''Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia'' 1904).<ref>Sarah P. Monks, "Variability and Autotomy of Phataria" [https://archive.org/details/jstor-4063000 ''Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia''] 56(August 1904): 596-601.</ref> She was listed as a member of the [[Woods Hole Marine Biological Laboratory]] in 1888, and in 1894 as a founding member of the laboratory's Biological Association.<ref name="Knatz" /> The snail ''[[Fusinus monksae]]'' is believed to have been named for her.<ref name="Knatz" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hansson |first1=Hans G. |title=Biographical Etymology of Marine Organism Names. M |url=http://www.tmbl.gu.se/libdb/taxon/personetymol/petymol.m |website=www.tmbl.gu.se |accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref>
==Personal life== Monks had a cottage named "Phataria" on Sea Pansy Bay in the Los Angeles Harbor, next door to the cottage of her friend, [[Charles Fletcher Lummis]]. She donated her library of scientific publications and other materials to the [[Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County]] in 1915.<ref name="Knatz" /> She died in San Pedro on July 10, 1926, aged 85 years.<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/clip/15235529/sarah_p_monks_1926/ "Authoress Dies"] ''Santa Ana Register'' (July 12, 1926): 1. via [[Newspapers.com]]{{open access}}</ref><ref name="Creese2000">{{cite book|first=Mary R.S.|last= Creese|title=Ladies in the Laboratory? American and British Women in Science, 1800-1900: A Survey of Their Contributions to Research|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=amtGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA134|date=2000|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-585-27684-7|page=134}}</ref>
